<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 94 / MacGregor admits he intervened in rail pay dispute: Train
drivers threaten to hold strike ballot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, KEVIN BROWN and STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John MacGregor, the trans-port secretary, admitted yesterday he had
intervened in the rail dispute to warn Railtrack management not to breach
the government's public sector pay bill freeze.
His admission, which came as the rail network was paralysed by the 24-hour
strike, followed the withdrawal earlier this week of a negotiating
'proposal' by Railtrack to pay its signalling staff a 5.7 per cent rise.
Further conflict on the railways was threatened yesterday by the train
drivers' union Aslef. Its annual conference threw out a 2.5 per cent pay
settlement recommended by its leaders. Delegates warned if it was not
increased the drivers would be balloted for strike action.
Until Mr MacGregor's remarks on the Railtrack proposal, the government had
repeatedly denied allegations that it put pressure on the company to drop
the higher offer.
Mr MacGregor said he had told Railtrack, the new public sector company
responsible for the railway infrastructure, of 'the general government
position' on public sector pay within the past few days.
Mr Frank Dobson, Labour's transport spokesman, said Mr MacGregor's comments
showed the rail strike was 'entirely the fault of the government'.
Although the rail network was at a virtual standstill yesterday, predicted
road chaos failed to materialise as thousands of commuters stayed at home.
Negotiations are expected during the next few days to try to prevent a
second 24-hour stoppage by railway signal staff announced for next
Wednesday.
Both Mr Bob Horton, Railtrack chairman, and Mr Jimmy Knapp, general
secretary of the RMT rail union, said they hoped talks could continue
despite further public argument over who was to blame for the dispute. Mr
Horton denied that signalling staff had been offered 5.7 per cent and he
repudiated a memorandum from his production manager for Railtrack South that
said it had. 'That was an internal memorandum from an over-zealous, very
junior manager,' he said.
The RMT union issued another Railtrack document, Proposal to RMT, handed to
the union last week by Mr Chris Leah, the company's main negotiator. It
makes clear that Railtrack wants 'to restore the relativities of signalling
grades as detailed in the RMT claim of February 9'. It adds: 'This figure
which is set at 5.7 per cent will then be cascaded throughout all the
signalling grades. This new basic rate will then be the base position for
stage two discussions.' The Railtrack 'proposal' emphasised that the
signalling staff would have to agree to work flexibly and open up jobs to
wider recruitment.
What seems to have happened is that Mr Horton and his board decided to
overrule Railtrack's negotiators by withdrawing the 5.7 per cent interim pay
offer. Instead they decided all the issues raised by the union should be
dealt with in one set of negotiations.
Few upsets, Page 7
</TEXT>
