<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUN 94 / Clarke promises economy will not boom and bust: Future rise
in interest rates indicated by Bank governor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, PHILIP COGGAN and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, last night pledged that the government
would not steer Britain's economic recovery into a new boom and bust cycle
by generating a 'fraudulent, inflationary, feel good' factor among the
electorate.
Delivering the annual Mansion House speech in the City, Mr Clarke moved
decisively to scotch suggestions that the government might opt for more
expansionary economic policies in the wake of recent electoral disasters.
After a day in which official figures pointed to a steady, low inflation
recovery from recession, he made clear that public spending cuts would take
precedence over tax cuts. He declared that it would be 'very bad politics'
for the government to risk more inflation.
'We will cut taxes again, but only when we can afford to do so,' Mr Clarke
said. 'The public are usually more sensible than politicians and the press.
They will not put their confidence in a government that cuts taxes before
getting borrowing under control.'
The Mansion House speech has traditionally been the occasion for chancellors
to expound on monetary policy. But last night, Mr Clarke chose a broader
brush approach, partly because the details of monetary policy are in the
public domain following the government's decision to publish the minutes of
the chancellor's meetings with Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of
England.
It was left to Mr George to dwell briefly on monetary matters, with a clear
warning that UK interest rates would have to move upwards at some
unspecified moment in the future.
When rates were raised it would be 'to maintain the (economic) expansion at
a sustainable pace', Mr George said. The Bank's purpose was 'not to leave
the tightening of policy so late that the economy is brought to a juddering
halt by a much larger interest rise than would otherwise be needed'.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, later claimed the speeches showed Mr
George did not find Mr Clarke's policies 'credible'. He added that the
government could not be trusted now on taxes or interest rates.
Yesterday's figures on unemployment, inflation and earnings suggested the
economic recovery is being sustained. Average earnings slowed to an
underlying average annual rate of 3 3/4 per cent in April from 4 per cent in
March, calming City fears that the Bank might soon have to push up short
term interest rates.
The news on the retail prices front was also positive, with the annual
'headline' rate of inflation staying unchanged at 2.6 per cent in May
compared with April. Although the underlying measure of retail price
inflation quickened to 2.5 per cent last month from 2.3 per cent in April,
analysts said the increase partly reflected seasonal factors.
Meanwhile, a seasonally adjusted 20,100 drop in unemployment to 2.66m in May
reinforced the picture of a steady recovery. The fall, for the fourth month
in a row, cut the jobless rate among benefit claimants to 9.4 per cent of
the workforce in May from 9.5 per cent the month before.
There continued, however, to be a discrepancy between the claimant figures
and those for the workforce in employment. The latter showed that the number
of people in employment fell by 92,000 in 1994's first quarter.
Mr John Prescott, shadow employment secretary, said: 'The government's own
statistics show in 1993, while 201,000 people came off unemployment
benefits, employment increased by only 19,000. The rest disappeared.'
Inflation, unemployment and earnings details, Page 8
Kenneth Clarke and Eddie George speeches, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 21 Lex, Page 22
Bonds, Page 31
Currencies, Page 33
London stocks, Page 42
