<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Benign CPI data bolster Dow
rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US shares rallied yesterday on economic news which suggested that the
Federal Reserve was unlikely to tighten monetary policy again in the next
few weeks, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 31.71 higher at 3,814.83, its
first close above 3,800 since March 24. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 3.27
ahead at 462.37. New York SE volume came to 288.5m shares and advances
outpaced falls by 1,269 to 820. The American SE composite gained 1.46 at
442.65 and the Nasdaq composite added 4.28 at 735.98.
The catalyst for the morning's sharp upturn was the May consumer price
index, released by the Labor Department just before the markets opened. The
CPI showed a benign 0.2 per cent increase for the month, or a 2.5 per cent
gain on an annualised basis. When the volatile food and energy sectors were
excluded, consumer prices were up 0.3 per cent. Both figures matched the
consensus forecasts of economists, relieving anxieties over a potential
sell-off in bonds.
In the event, Treasuries posted moderate gains, as news of a 0.2 per cent
slide in May retail sales reinforced the conviction that the economy was not
overheating.
Still, the gains made in the equity markets overshadowed the progress made
by bonds during the morning, as stocks continued to assert a measure of
independence.
Equity investors viewed the morning's news as favourable because it
increased the odds that the Fed would wait until the end of the summer
before lifting rates again.
Such a scenario was particularly supportive for stocks most vulnerable to a
slowing economy. The same group was in the vanguard of Monday's rally.
Caterpillar, which had led the Dow industrials during the winter, showed
fresh signs of vigour, jumping Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars 109 3/8 . United
Technologies rose Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 67 1/2 and Allied Signal advanced
Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 37 5/8 .
The Big Three car makers also powered ahead on the favourable fundamentals.
In telecommunications, Sprint dropped Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 36 7/8 after
announcing that France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom had agreed to take a 20
per cent stake in the company. Analysts said possible regulatory obstacles
to the deal may have scared away investors. In addition, there was some
concern over the dilutive impact of Sprint's proposed issue of 85m new
shares under terms of the agreement.
Exxon continued to feel the repercussions of Monday's court ruling which may
allow plaintiffs to pursue an estimated Dollars 15bn in punitive claims for
damages arising from the Exxon Valdez oil spill.
Analysts were divided in their recommendations following the decision. AG
Edwards lowered its rating on the issue from buy to hold, but Prudential
Securities urged its clients to add to their holdings. In the cross-current,
Exxon slipped Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 59 and led the NYSE's most active list
on volume of 4.9m shares.
Canada
Toronto stocks closed lower as the 'Quebec malaise' continued to hound
equities. Analysts said mounting uncertainty over the future of the
French-speaking province is pushing Toronto shares into a downward spiral.
In contrast to Wall Street buoyancy, the TSE 300 index ended 8.2 lower at
4,198.6 and falls led rises by 394 to 351 after volume of 56.2m shares.
Eight of the 14 stock groups showed increases, however, led by golds, up
1.39 per cent. Mining and banking fell 1.34 and 1.91 per cent respectively.
Mexico
Equities finished slightly firmer after a roller coaster session, with
investors still showing signs of nerves. The market had tumbled 4 per cent
on Monday following the rejection by the Zapatista rebels in Chiapas at the
weekend of the latest peace initiative.
The IPC index was finally ahead 9.8 points yesterday at 2,300.9 and volume
was a moderate 1.18bn new pesos on 107.7m shares traded.
Brazil
Sao Paulo saw high volume ahead of today's futures index settlement;
equities closed 2.4 per cent up in local currency terms after a 4 per cent
gain seen around noon.
The Bovespa index was up a net 704 points at 30,173. Traders said turnover
was unusually large at Cr447bn due to a high volume of option deals.
