<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Berisford Pounds 5.8m in red after
provision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Berisford International, the former commodities and property group which
paid Pounds 56m for the Magnet kitchen and joinery business in March,
yesterday reported pre-tax losses of Pounds 5.8m for the half year to March
31 compared with profits of Pounds 400,000.
The result was after a Pounds 9.7m provision covering the write-off of
Bristar Trading, Berisford's cocoa trading associate. If any cash is
recouped from this business it will come back through the profit and loss
account.
At the operating level Berisford achieved profits of Pounds 3.7m (Pounds
1.5m losses). Magnet contributed Pounds 1.4m of the profit, but Mr Alan
Bowkett, chief executive, stressed that March was traditionally Magnet's
best month as January sales turned into profits. Even so, Mr John Sclater,
chairman, remained confident of predicting the payment of a final dividend.
Turnover rose to Pounds 51.3m (Pounds 47.3m) with Magnet contributing Pounds
16.9m. Losses per share were 4.4p (0.2p earnings).
Since the half-year end, Mr Bowkett said, Magnet had remained profitable in
spite of a repositioning programme in April and May when advertising was
stopped. Branches now served both trade and retail customers and ranges had
been rationalised.
Magnet's workforce had been cut from 2,600 to 2,000, with 400 jobs going in
the shops and 130 in the factories. More than Pounds 4m had been invested in
new kitchen manufacturing equipment. One new outlet has been opened while
Berisford has identified 50 places where it could open branches.
The group is also continuing to realise some 'old Berisford' assets,
including properties with a book value of Pounds 16m.
It aims to retain its US agribusinesses, although these are expected to
incur losses in the second half, in order to protect its US tax losses which
total Pounds 434m. A senior executive is being posted to New York to search
out an acquisition in the US.
Following the rights issue, which funded the Magnet purchase, net cash was
Pounds 53.8m at March 31, which has since risen to Pounds 54.7m, and net
assets were Pounds 214.7m.
Mr Robert Pritzker, has resigned as a non-executive director, although his
brother Jay is remaining on the board. The two are large shareholders in the
group.
</TEXT>
