<DOCNO>FT942-3351</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EFODGADDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A varied and enticing night. BBC2's computer series, The Net, investigates
the panic about 'computer porn' and its supposed easy access to children and
asks whether this reflects reality or adult techno-fear (8.00). Also on BBC2
the 'Screen Two' drama In The Cold Light Of Day has a most impressive cast
including Stephanie Cole, Bernard Hepton, Ronald Pickup and Frances Barber.
The story sounds attractively weird: switching from the 1930s and the
erection of a pylon in a suburban garden in northern England to the 1980s
and the revelation of a 'a love that dared not speak its name ..' (9.00).
Prior to returning to his native New Zealand, Bryan Gould who may (or may
not) be kicking himself for quitting British politics just before the Labour
party needed a new leader, appears in Frontline to offer his thoughts on
British politics (9.00 C4). Inside Story does not go all the way and
question the legitimacy of what Sir Peter Medawar called 'one of the most
stupendous confidence tricks of the century' (psychoanalysis) but it does
look into false memory syndrome (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
