<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Fewer directors may face charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of prosecutions and disqualification petitions against company
directors this year may fail to meet official objectives because of new
guidelines intended to clear a backlog of outstanding cases, the Department
of Trade and Industry said yesterday, Andrew Jack writes.
The department, commenting on an internal memo sent by the senior official
receiver to Insolvency Service offices, said it was possible that
prosecutions would fall in line with a fall in the number of investigations
of liquidations and bankruptcies.
The senior official receiver has written asking staff in offices around the
UK to identify in the next four weeks an additional 11,000 cases to be
closed - more than half the total closed last year.
The guidance said an average of an hour should be enough to examine cases
and decide whether they could be closed. It said staff need not look for
possible offences or areas for investigation.
However, the principal union in the agency has sent guidance to its members
suggesting that this time is inadequate and advising them to take adequate
care in their scrutiny of documents.
The bulletin, being circulated to members of the insolvency service branch
of the Institute of Professional and Managerial Staffs, the civil service
union, says: 'Examiners must not be used to sausage-machine cases for
closing by turning a blind eye to possible assets or other matters.'
</TEXT>
