<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Banham digs in for the liberation of Blackpool
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Blackburn, Blackpool, Lancaster, Portsmouth, Slough and an enlarged Reading
will become self-governing under plans to redraw the English local
government map announced yesterday by the Local Government Commission.
Blueprints for Berkshire, Hampshire and Lancashire, following five other
counties announced on Monday, signal a continued intention to replace the
two-tier system of counties and districts in non-metropolitan England.
County councils in many areas would be abolished and existing districts
merged to form unitary authorities.
The commission risked a row with the government by recommending that the
two-tier system should stay in place for all of Hampshire except Southampton
and Portsmouth.
The commission's detailed recommendations, which will go to public
consultation, are:
Berkshire: The county, and all except one of its districts, agreed a
proposal for four unitary authorities which the commission has now endorsed.
Slough and an 'expanded' Reading would become unitaries, while Bracknell
Forest, Windsor and Maidenhead, and most of Wokingham would merge to create
Royal East Berkshire. Newbury would also be unitary, and would take in a few
Hampshire parishes.
Hampshire: If the first option of leaving the county unchanged outside its
two biggest cities is rejected, the commission's favourite alternative of
seven unitary authorities involves radical restructuring, and would be
fiercely opposed by the county.
The unitaries would be New Forest; Basingstoke and Deane with the north part
of Test Valley; Hart and Rushmoor; Winchester, East Hampshire and the south
part of Test Valley; Southampton and Eastleigh; Fareham and Gosport; and
Portsmouth and Havant.
Financial consultants described the first option as 'the worst of all
worlds', as Portsmouth and Southampton attract proportionately more
government grants than the rest of the county. The shrunken county council
might therefore suffer a disproportionately sharp reduction in grant.
Lancashire: Eight unitary authorities are the commission's preferred choice
for Lancashire, but local people can opt instead for six or seven. They can
also keep the status quo of a county council with 14 second-tier districts.
The eight would be Lancaster; Blackburn (represented in parliament by
Labour's local government spokesman, Mr Jack Straw, who favours unitary
councils); Wyre and Fylde; West Lancashire; Chorley, Preston and South
Ribble; Blackpool; Hyndburn and Ribble Valley; and Burnley, Pendle and
Rossendale.
Annual savings are put between Pounds 1m and Pounds 8m, with set-up costs of
Pounds 21m to Pounds 28m.
The six-authority proposal would cost as much to set up but would save more
 -between Pounds 9m and Pounds 16m a year. But it would require Blackpool to
join Wyre and Fylde, and Blackburn to merge with Hyndburn and Ribble Valley.
The mergers would be accepted by the commission if there were support for
them, but neither is likely to find favour in the rural areas of Wyre, Fylde
and Ribble Valley, the last of which is unlikely to welcome Hyndburn anyway.
The case for the status quo will be vigorously fought by Lancashire county
council, which secured a judgment from the High Court to ensure that this
option was included in consultation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
