<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / EU seeks views on Cadbury link with lottery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission is calling for comments on commercial agreements
that link Cadbury Schweppes products to the operation of the National
Lottery.
The confectionery company is a member of the Camelot consortium that is due
to launch the UK's National Lottery in November.
Under the terms of the agreement with Camelot Cadbury Schweppes has the
right to try to advertise its products in connection with the prize-draws -
a connection that could be extended to television for an agreed fee.
The plan is that confectionery displays carrying the Cadbury name will be
offered as part of the lottery terminal which will dispense and authenticate
tickets.
The commission said yesterday that it was examining the consortium venture
to see whether it contravened EU rules on free and fair competition - normal
practice for any joint ventures that threaten, however remotely, to create a
dominant position in the market.
The commission said: 'This is purely normal.' It added that a decision would
be taken in the next two months, well before the lottery's November start
date.
Camelot emphasised yesterday that retailers would be free to reject the
Cadbury's display and have a terminal on its own. Retailers could accept the
display and fill it with products of other companies.
In calling for comments on any aspect of Camelot's plans the commission
notes that Camelot is obliged 'to use reasonable endeavours to promote the
use by retailers of a display unit supplied by Cadbury Schweppes to hold the
lottery terminal and to display Cadbury Schweppes branded confectionery'.
However, the commission added that retailers selling lottery tickets would
be under no contractual obligation to go along with the Cadbury Schweppes
plan.
Cadbury Schweppes said yesterday it was fully aware that the European
Commission was looking at the lottery agreement and did not believe this
would present a problem.
</TEXT>
