The monthly industrial survey, for example, includes only five subjective
questions. Although the quarterly surveys are more detailed, including
evaluations of expectations over the next four months, the answers are kept
to the 'better' or 'worse' criterion, and do not demand precise estimates.
For some companies, at least, the tactic has worked. Mr Philip Aiken,
managing director of Gas Europe in BOC, said: 'The forms they send you are
very user-friendly. My 11-year-old daughter could fill them in' He said he
completed the survey because he found the results valuable.
But as Mr Aiken pointed out that the flip side of this approach was that the
vagueness of the questions meant that companies could answer them in varying
ways. 'I do sometimes wonder about the quality of the data. I suspect some
people might answer depending on how they feel that day,' he said.
Most companies insist that their response is more scientific - according to
the CBI senior management answer the survey in more than 80 per cent of
cases. But Mr Junankar admitted that companies could vary in the way they
interpreted issues such as 'business constraints' - and, more crucially,
their concepts of 'normal' business activity.
Mr Aiken, for example, judges whether business has improved by looking for
changes of 2 per cent or more, usually based on a year-on-year plan, and
does not include labour availability in his assessment of business
constraints.
Mr Derek Sutton, company secretary of Loake Brothers, a Northamptonshire
shoemaker, defines what is 'normal' by 'running my eye over the last couple
of years'. Changes of 10 per cent in either direction are considered to be
'better' or 'worse'. He considers that labour contraints, such as the
availability of workers, are central to any definition of business
constraints.
Mr Edward Roberts, of the spring makers Heath Springs, takes a more
computerised approach, calculating the productivity of his workforce down to
the last penny.
An economist who answers the survey for a large construction group said that
he responded by comparing the present performance with a five or 10-year
period - a measure that left him concluding that activity in the last three
years had been 'below normal', in spite of small interim rises.
The CBI points out that these variations do not appear to affect the data
significantly. Indeed, some economists say the surveys often provide a
better economic guide than the official statistics.
Some companies suggest that the CBI should issue more precise guidelines or
ask for a numerical evaluation. The CBI is reluctant to do this, since
changing the way companies answer would cause a break in the series.
Mr Junankar suggested that analysts should be aware that a company's concept
of 'normal' could change over time, and give more focus to shorter-term
comparisons of changes in business mood.
This message could prove pertinent as economists debate how far the UK
economy is proceeding along the path of a 'normal' recovery.
</TEXT>
<XX>
