<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Clients lash out at professionals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professionals overcharge and provide a generally poor service to their
clients, says a survey of companies' views published yesterday.
Only half of nearly 200 small companies felt accountants provided a useful
letter to management to accompany the annual audit, according to a survey
sponsored by Levy Gee, the accountancy firm.
Just 19 per cent of businesses felt their bankers offered value for money,
while half expressed dissatisfaction over value from their solicitors and 43
per cent from their accountants.
Few advisers explained adequately how their fees were calculated, and
accountants' charges were singled out for the most criticism.
One respondent said there were often 'too many round figures for comfort'.
One company reported that accountants are 'patronisingly expensive and tend
to try and blind one with jargon'.
Another complained that they 'continually search for angles to overcharge'.
Bankers and solicitors were criticised for failing to keep clients
up-to-date with important developments. Three-quarters of companies surveyed
believed that their bankers did not understand their business sector,
compared with two-thirds for solicitors and 43 per cent for accountants.
Two-fifths of bankers met expectations for quality and deadlines, compared
with 62 per cent of solicitors and 70 per cent of accountants.
Only three-quarters of the companies felt senior bankers were easily
accessible. Nearly all felt that executives and partners in law and
accountancy practices were easily accessible.
Levy Gee concluded that advisers needed to anticipate what customers
required and be more active in helping businesses develop plans.
The firm urged professionals to be more open about fees and charges, and to
adopt a flexible approach when companies are struggling.
The Role of Professional Advisers and the Changing Requirements of Business.
Fiona Inchbald, c/o Levy Gee, 66 Wigmore St, London W1H 0HQ. Pounds 25
</TEXT>
