<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Siemens wins power deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Power, the privatised electricity generator, has awarded to Siemens
of Germany a fiercely contested contract to build a 1,350MW gas-fired power
station at Didcot in Oxfordshire.
The turnkey contract for the design, construction and commissioning of the
plant is valued at less than Pounds 400m. Mr John Baker, National Power's
chief executive, said yesterday that he believed it was the UK's most
competitive power plant project.
Announcement of the award comes a few days after PowerGen, the UK's other
big electricity generator, said it was paying Pounds 441m in advance for its
gas-fired power station at Connah's Quay, North Wales, which is being built
by the Anglo-French GEC Alsthom engineering group.
The Didcot B contract is the first for Siemens from National Power, whose
other combined cycle gas turbine (CCGT) stations have been ordered from
Zurich-based Asea Brown Boveri and GEC Alsthom.
But the German company has built two gas-fired stations for PowerGen, and Mr
Juergen Gehrels, chief executive of Siemens in the UK, said yesterday: 'We
believe that our successful track record in delivering total turnkey
projects, on time and to budget, was a key factor in (National Power's)
decision.'
National Power is clearly delighted with the deal it has struck with Siemens
 -two years ago, it was thought the station would cost about Pounds 450m.
But the contract has been held up by a public inquiry and the UK
government's review of the coal industry.
Didcot B is scheduled to be the largest and most efficient of National
Power's CCGT stations, and will be built in two separate modules alongside
the existing 2,000MW coal-fired station at Didcot. Commercial operation is
due to start in 1997.
The new station is the next step in National Power's programme to upgrade
its generating capacity with about 5,000MW of CCGT plant by the end of the
decade, to meet tightening environmental standards.
</TEXT>
