<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / House sales fall by 10% over year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
House sales last month fell by more than a tenth compared with May last year
according to a survey of more than 4,000 estate agents' offices handling
about a half of all sales.
The survey by the Ombudsman for Corporate Estate Agents (OCEA), covering 26
of the largest estate agency chains, provides further evidence of a sharp
setback in the housing recovery.
Mr Peter Constable, OCEA's chairman, blamed tax increases and the
introduction of higher interest rates for fixed-rate mortgages for a 12.4
per cent decline in net sales compared with May last year.
Sales were also 4.9 per cent lower than April this year. A sale is recorded
if finance has been arranged, solicitors have been instructed and no chain
is involved, according to OCEA, which began compiling figures in 1991.
Mr Constable said new instructions were 2.6 per cent lower than a year ago
and 6.5 per cent lower than the previous month. He said: 'The earlier froth
has now been eliminated from the market by tax increases and by the
hardening of interest rates for fixed rate mortgages.'
</TEXT>
