<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Ministers at loggerheads over timetable for legislation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers are considering including fresh legislation to reform the Child
Support Agency in next year's legislative timetable.
The debate over its reform is taking place at a time of wide-ranging
differences between cabinet ministers on whether plans for virtually all
radical legislation should be shelved in favour of measures designed to
rebuild a reputation for competent government.
With the process of whittling down the long list of bills proposed by
individual government departments about to start in earnest, proponents of
various controversial measures are arguing that the next parliamentary
session provides the last chance to enact proposals before the next general
election.
In addition, with an election likely in 1996, they believe it is too risky
to leave projects such as CSA reform, Post Office privatisation and an
'omnibus' privatisation bill (which would remove the need for separate
'paving' legislation before each sale of public assets) until the session
starting in autumn 1995.
But their views are opposed by consolidators. In the case of the Child
Support Agency the consolidators argue that it is not yet clear what changes
need to be made.
Earlier this year the government introduced a number of modifications in the
way the agency functions. These included enabling absent fathers facing big
increases in maintenance to pay bills in stages. Mr Peter Lilley, social
security secretary, has said he is determined not to be 'rushed into
further, inappropriate changes'.
With the government already committed to a wide-ranging pensions bill, the
next session could be a busy one in the Commons for social security
ministers.
They are also expected to share responsibility with colleagues in the
Department of Employment for a bill implementing the proposed job seekers'
allowance, to replace income support and unemployment benefit from 1996.
Other likely candidates for inclusion are a bill paving the way for the
abolition of Health Service regional authorities and another criminal
justice bill related to alleged miscarriages of justice.
Officials expect this to be much more tightly drafted than this year's
criminal justice bill, which was used by MPs to force votes on a range of
home affairs-related issues.
Ministers are also considering whether to include a bill setting up a new
environmental protection agency, in line with a manifesto commitment, and a
Northern Ireland police bill, in a move that would be welcomed by unionists.
A housing reform bill - probably including the abolition of rules allowing
people classed as 'statutorily homeless' to receive an automatic right to a
council house - is a further candidate, as is a bill to bring British Summer
Time into line with European time.
Government business managers involved in drafting next year's timetable face
the added complication of needing to make allowance for a European bill to
permit the enlargement of the Union.
There is still no indication of when ministers will be able to come forward
with legislation, included in the last Queen's Speech, giving force to
changes in the European Union's system of own resources. This will increase
Britain's contribution to the EU budget in line with the agreement reached
at the Edinburgh European Council in December 1992. It will be opposed by
Eurosceptics.
Officials suggest the government may seek to increase its room for manoeuvre
by omitting any explicit reference to Child Support Agency reform from the
Queen's Speech but including the usual catch-all clause committing the
government to 'other measures'.
This would increase pressure on business managers to keep short the list of
bills specifically identified in the speech.
</TEXT>
