<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Spurs hit by Cup ban and big fine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tottenham Hotspur was last night banned from the FA Cup for a year and fined
Pounds 600,000. In addition, 12 points were docked from its score next
season.
The penalty, the biggest ever imposed by the Football Association, was over
irregular payments to players.
The FA also ordered the north London club - which was saved from financial
disaster in 1991 by Mr Alan Sugar's injection of cash when he formed the
then 'dream ticket' with club manager Terry Venables - to pay the costs of
its investigation. The FA looked at 40 charges relating to loans made to
players in the 1980s.
Mr Sugar, the chairman, Mr Colin Sandy, Tottenham's financial director, and
Mr Peter Barnes, the club secretary, spent several hours at yesterday's
hearing held at Wembley, before the fine was announced. Previously, the
largest fine for a similar offence was Pounds 105,000 imposed on Chelsea in
1991.
The punishment is a severe financial setback to the club, which only just
escaped relegation to the first division last season. The loss from FA Cup
exclusion, with possible relegation next season - which will be more
difficult to avoid starting with a 12-point deficit - could amount to
millions.
Mr Bernie Kingsley, co-ordinator of the Tottenham Independent Supporters'
Association, last night demanded that the FA clarify its ruling. He said:
'The FA needs to make absolutely clear which charges Tottenham is guilty of
and who they consider responsible so the club can take its own action.'
The FA has said only that it found Tottenham guilty of a range of irregular
payments. Mr Kingsley also argued that loans were not against the
association's rules and that the breach was technical, in that they were not
reported.
Tottenham Hotspur shares have slid as the FA hearing has approached.
Yesterday, with the market closed before the fine was announced, the price
stood at 80p.
The hearing comes just more than a year after Mr Sugar went to the High
Court to oust Mr Venables, now the England coach, from his position as chief
executive of Tottenham.
A Tottenham spokesman said last night that the club was shocked at the
ruling's severity, and added: 'Spurs provided all the information on the
offences - all of which took place before Alan Sugar took control -
voluntarily.'
Mr Sugar said: 'I was always brought up to believe honesty is the best
policy, and have followed that throughout my career. The punishment dished
out today is a bitter pill to swallow if you adopt that policy as I have
done.'
</TEXT>
