<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Censure for Allied Dunbar advert
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Allied Dunbar, the life company, has been told by the Advertising Standards
Authority to withdraw an advertisement featuring a funeral because of the
'severe distress' it caused some readers.
The advertisement, headlined 'Every two minutes someone dies of heart
disease', pictured a burial service viewed from the bottom of a grave
looking upwards, with mourners and a priest looking down. The ASA said 15
complaints were received from people who found the advertisement 'emotive,
in extreme bad taste, an appeal to fear, and distressing'.
Separately, the ASA upheld a complaint against Allied Dunbar over its direct
mailing. The complainant objected to the continual receipt of unrequested
mailings, even though he had been assured by the company that his details
were on a 'no contact' list.
