<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Reliefs granted to laws on competing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further measures to relieve the burden of competition laws on businesses
were announced yesterday by Mr Neil Hamilton, deregulation minister, Robert
Rice writes.
The government proposes to cut the maximum time allowed for ministers to
consider whether to refer a pre-notified merger to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission for full investigation from 45 days to 35 days.
It is also planning to relieve small businesses from the burden of
investigation for anti-competitive conduct under the 1980 Competition Act by
raising the turnover threshold below which they escape scrutiny from Pounds
5m to Pounds 10m.
The government has rejected a call by MPs to give the proposed new
deregulation committee the power to summon ministers. It said in response to
a report by the Commons procedure committee that the power would be
'unprecedented' and 'unnecessary'.
</TEXT>
