<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Clarke set to impose more spending cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke will today warn cabinet colleagues in charge of
Whitehall's big spending departments to expect a further round of cuts in
their budgets.
His stance will foreshadow the third consecutive year of tight public-sector
pay restraint and the possibility of a new batch of measures to curb the
Pounds 85bn social security budget.
Amid calls from the Tory right for an early government commitment to tax
cuts, the chancellor is preparing to use his speech at the Mansion House to
tighten the framework for this summer's spending round.
The main thrust of his annual speech to bankers will seek to underline the
government's seriousness about sticking to its medium-term inflation target.
The Treasury wants to dispel any idea in the financial markets that recent
differences in emphasis between Mr Clarke and Mr Eddie George, the governor
of the Bank of England, might represent a softening in the government's
resolve.
In spite of calls from rightwing cabinet ministers for early tax cuts, the
Treasury is dismissing suggestions it might abandon the second stage of the
imposition of value added tax on domestic fuel.
But Mr Clarke is keen to impress on cabinet colleagues that the overall
spending figures which were set out in his Budget last November represented
'ceilings' rather than targets for the government's spending.
The Treasury set a global Whitehall figure of Pounds 263bn for 1995-96 and
Pounds 272bn for 1996-97, representing increases in real terms of less than
1 per cent each year.
But Mr Clarke believes the improved inflation outlook since last autumn
allows for a further reduction in the cash figures and the establishment of
a still tougher target for 1997-98.
The cabinet's EDX spending committee is due to report to the full cabinet
next week. The Treasury wants that meeting to endorse its strategy of a
tighter squeeze.
But ministers close to EDX said that because of higher-than-predicted
increases in 'demand-led' expenditure in areas such as social security and
education, cash reductions will be required in other departmental budgets.
Some ministers want Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, to take
fresh action to contain his budget, with tighter limits on the growth in
housing benefits and curbs on mortgage interest payments for the unemployed.
Others are voicing frustration at the Treasury's unwillingness to ease the
pressure on spending by relaxing the present constraints on private-sector
involvement in public-sector projects.
</TEXT>
