<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Shake-up in policy team for Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Clinton administration is to undertake a further shake-up of its foreign
affairs team, with a complete reshuffle of personnel in charge of European
policy.
Mr Richard Holbrooke, a senior diplomat in the Carter administration and now
the US ambassador to Germany, will be recalled to replace Mr
Stephen Oxman, the assistant secretary of state for European and Canadian
affairs.
This is likely to be seen as one more old Washington hand taking the place
of another friend of President Bill Clinton, because Mr Oxman attended Yale
law school with the president.
Also, Mr Alexander Vershbow, Mr Oxman's deputy, will move to the White House
to take over from Ms Jenonne Walker as head of European affairs at the
National Security Council.
The positions are central to the formulation of the US administration's
policy on Bosnia, among other issues.
Ms Walker is to become ambassador to the Czech Republic, and Mr Oxman is
also expected to be offered an embassy.
