<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / World Trade News: Foreign chip share steady
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The foreign share of Japan's semiconductor market was 20.7 per cent in the
first quarter of 1994, unchanged from the fourth quarter of 1993 and
slightly above the 20 per cent target set in the second US-Japan
semiconductor trade agreement, signed in 1991, writes Louise Kehoe in San
Francisco.
Since the adoption of the first semiconductor trade agreement in 1986, which
for the first time established market share as a measure of market access,
the foreign share has risen by 8.5 per cent. However, over the past two
years the foreign share data have varied significantly from quarter to
quarter reaching a record high in the fourth quarter of 1993.
US semiconductor industry officials called for renewed efforts. We need to
'ensure that foreign access to the Japanese market moves beyond the 20 per
cent mark in order to realise the goal of a truly competitive Japanese
market,' said Andrew Procassini, president of the (US) Semiconductor
Industry Association. The trade agreement calls for 'gradual and steady
progress' through 1996, he noted.
</TEXT>
