<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / London likely to bear brunt of today's rail strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY, ROBERT TAYLOR and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London commuters prepared to bear the brunt of today's 24-hour rail strike
as it emerged last night that the government was understood to have blocked
a 5.7 per cent pay offer for the 4,600 signal staff at the centre of the
dispute.
Railtrack, which runs the network, is believed to have put forward the offer
in talks with the RMT union earlier this week.
But the company was later told by the Transport Department - backed by the
Treasury - that the government would block any pay increase unless it was
fully funded by productivity.
The prospect of an above-inflation pay offer is said to have horrified
ministers, and Railtrack was told to demonstrate that staff were still
working in the public sector and must abide by government pay policy.
Ministers decided to intervene after concluding that Railtrack's
'inexperienced' negotiators were likely to concede too much to the RMT in an
attempt to keep the trains running.
RMT leader Mr Jimmy Knapp last night accused Railtrack of 'reneging' on a
5.7 per cent pay offer. He had earlier suggested that the government may
have been behind Railtrack withdrawing the offer and replacing it with one
for 2.5 per cent.
'Railtrack have dealt a body blow to industrial relations and the integrity
of the company is in tatters,' he said.
Labour's transport spokesman, Mr Brian Wilson, accused the government of
'gross irresponsibility' in 'sabotaging' the prospect of a settlement to the
dispute.
However, Mr Chris Leah, Railtrack's chief negotiator, denied that the
company had offered 5.7 per cent. Railtrack added last night: 'This decision
was taken by the board alone. We are a commercial company and we have to
live with commercial realities.'
In the Commons, Mr John Major condemned the strike and said extra parking
would be made available in London. The Department of Transport said there
would be 10,000 more spaces at locations such as Hyde Park and Regents Park.
In spite of the strike, most of London's Underground system will be running.
Police and motoring organisations advised people to share cars or stagger
journeys.
The London Weather Centre has forecast another sunny day today which could
persuade people to stay away from work.
Only 15 underground stations will be affected out of a total of 273. London
Transport said there would be no Tube services on the northern stretch of
the Bakerloo Line from Queens Park to Harrow and Wealdstone or in south
London on the District Line between Turnham Green and Richmond and East
Putney and Wimbledon.
Out of London's two main airports, Gatwick is expected to be hit hardest, as
its main service into the capital is a Railtrack line to Victoria. It is
expecting 54,000 arrivals today, of which 24 per cent would normally travel
on the Gatwick Express.
Heathrow will be less affected as it is connected to London by underground.
Today's strike is the first serious challenge to the new railway system
which is being fashioned from the framework of British Rail.
