<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Low forecast for training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many employers plan to spend no more - and some will spend less - on
training in the next 20 years, says a report today from Huthwaite, the
training organisation.
The survey involved directors and senior managers from 150 companies
employing about 2.5m people. They were asked to assess the competitive
skills and training challenges facing their companies.
Twenty-five per cent of employers intended to spend no more on training
while 5 per cent said they intended to spend less. Only 12 per cent forecast
a big increase.
Companies appear to be introducing cheaper forms of training. More coaching
by line managers and supervisors will be the most popular development method
while classroom training will tend towards short and frequent modular
programmes. 'Open' or 'distance' learning - in which an individual typically
learns at his or her own pace from a package - will continue to grow in
significance.
Questioned about business organisation, respondents said that new employment
practices, such as part - time working or job-sharing, would not in
themselves do much to solve the unemployment problem as they did not
anticipate a wholesale switch to these.
20:20 Vision. Huthwaite, Hoober House, Wentworth, Rotherham, South Yorks.
Pounds 150.
</TEXT>
