<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / CBI welcome for 'changed' Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Howard Davies, the director-general of the CBI, yesterday underlined
Labour's growing appeal to traditional Tory voters by calling on business
leaders to pay serious attention to the party's economic policies.
In a speech to business leaders in London, Mr Davies said that Labour had
'changed in important ways' and was now willing to talk to business leaders
constructively.
His comments came as Mr Tony Blair, the front-runner for the Labour
leadership, underlined once again his commitment to turn Labour into the
party of 'law and order'.
Delivering the Police Foundation lecture at London's Guildhall, Mr Blair
said that his party's strategy to combat crime would be based on restoring
the sense of responsibility and respect among, in particular, young people.
In government, Labour would seek to provide the opportunity for individual
self-advancement but with that chance would come the 'duties of citizenship'
Disparaging the government's police reforms, Mr Blair said effective
policing depended on the re-establishment of strong and effective links
between police, local authorities, business and other organisations rooted
in local communities.
Other agencies should share responsibility with the police to create a
'proper partnership against crime'.
Mr Davies said that the party still had a number of policies with which the
CBI disagreed, such as its commitment to the social chapter of the
Maastricht treaty and a statutory minimum wage.
In one of the strongest indications yet of the rapprochement between Labour
and industry, Mr Davies said: 'It seems likely we shall be facing a Labour
leadership without any baggage from previous episodes in power, and with a
set of economic policies rather different from those which held sway in the
people's party for most of the 1980s.'
He added: 'It would be churlish not to recognise that the Labour party has
changed in important ways, and is offering a set of policies which, at the
very least deserve our attention. We shall give it.'
High street spending, Page 11
</TEXT>
