<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Labour shrugs off SNP threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday declared its determination to beat off the
challenge from the Scottish National party in the Monklands East
by-election, due to take place on June 30 and caused by the death last month
of John Smith.
Labour has gone for a quick by-election in the constituency, which mainly
comprises Airdrie, to the east of Glasgow, in order to try to prevent the
campaign by the SNP from gaining momentum.
It is defending a majority of 15,712 in what should be a safe seat, but
fears the SNP will profit from the bandwagon effect generated by its success
in last month's regional elections and its impressive victory this week in
the North East Scotland Euro-seat.
Yesterday Mr Alex Salmond, the SNP leader, acknowledged that his party had
'an electoral mountain to climb' but that it had the wind at its back and
had clambered some way up the hill already.
Mr George Robertson, shadow Scottish secretary, said that the SNP could not
be 'alternative Tories in the north-east of Scotland and then come down to
Airdrie and be alternative socialists. That won't wash here'.
The central belt of Scotland is much less promising territory for the SNP
than the more rural north-east.
However, it has the capacity to pour activists into by-elections and snatch
victory, as it did when it won the Glasgow Govan by-election from Labour in
1988.
In the regional elections the SNP won one of the two regional council seats
in the constituency. It will exploit claims that a small clique of Labour
councillors dominates Monklands district council.
Labour's candidate is Mrs Helen Liddell, a former secretary of the party in
Scotland who then worked for the late Robert Maxwell on the Daily Record,
the Scottish subsidiary of Mirror Group Newspapers.
The SNP on Monday night chose Mrs Kay Ullrich, a social worker and its
deputy defence spokesman, as its candidate.
The Tories have selected Mrs Susan Bell, a businesswoman who is
vice-president of the Scottish Tory Reform Group. The Liberal Democrat
candidate is Mr Stephen Gallagher, an NHS administrator.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
